<task>
Follow these instructions exactly:

## Step 1
For each property, determine which single component of `{{ contract_spec.contract_name }}` it most
directly constrains — that is, the component whose state variables and/or external entry points the
property actually talks about.

Decide this primarily from the component descriptions and the external entry points listed above:
match the nouns and operations the property mentions against each component's description and its
entry points, and pick the one whose responsibility most directly covers the property.

Only as a last resort — when the descriptions and entry points above genuinely leave a property
ambiguous between components — fall back to the source tools to read the relevant functions and
state of `{{ contract_spec.contract_name }}` and confirm which component owns the behavior.

## Step 2
For each property you can confidently place, produce a `matched` entry with:
- `property_id`: the exact id from the listing above,
- `component_name`: the exact name of one of the listed components of `{{ contract_spec.contract_name }}`,
- `methods`: the external entry points (function names/signatures) of that component that are
  involved in the property. For an invariant over contract state this may be empty.

If — and only if — a property cannot be confidently mapped to any single component (for example,
it concerns behavior that is not represented by any component, or it is too vague to place), put it
in `unmatched` with a concrete `reason`. Do not force a bad mapping; an honest `unmatched` entry is
preferable to a wrong one.

## Step 3
Deliver your result with the result tool. EVERY property_id from the listing must appear exactly
once, either in `matched` or in `unmatched` — never in both, never omitted.
</task>

